Inherited wit: An analysis of semantic similarities between works of political philosophers¶

In this project, we were given a massive dataset of quotes or excerpts from philosophers, from Aristotle to Wittgenstein.

It is quite likely that the teachings of one philosopher can influence another. To investigate connections between philosophers, this project aims to discover who influenced who. We will compare the key topics and phrases used by the various philosophers in the dataset and filter the data based on these findings. From there, if we can find philosophers that seem to have influenced other, then we can look into how their ideologies overlap.

The key tool that will be used to this end is semantic similarity. But what is semantic similarity and why should we care?

Semantic similarity is distinct from linguistic similarity in that it rather than simply looking at words used in a text, it considers the meanings of sentences when comparing their similarity.

For example, when comparing the quotes "whereof we do not yet know the issue." and "All this remains unknown.", an analysis of linguistic similarity would not detect any similarity at all because the two quotes have zero common words. However, an analysis of semantic similarity would show that these quotes are very similar, due to considering their meanings. This makes it a powerful and versatile tool for natural language processing, especially for a task such as this one.

Without further ado, let's dive into the analysis.

# # Function definitions
# # Same functions are contained in lib/relevant_functions.py
# # to import the functions from the folder if running locally
# # you could run the following 4 lines instead of defining the functions here
# import sys
# import os
# sys.path.append(os.getcwd()[:-3]+'lib')
# from relevant_functions import computeTF, computeIDF, computeTFIDF, wordclouder

def computeTF(wordDict, bagOfWords):
    tfDict = {}
    bagOfWordsCount = len(bagOfWords)
    for word, count in wordDict.items():
        tfDict[word] = count / float(bagOfWordsCount)
    return tfDict
  
def computeIDF(documents):
    import math
    N = len(documents)
    
    idfDict = dict.fromkeys(documents[0].keys(), 0)
    for document in documents:
        for word, val in document.items():
            if val > 0:
                idfDict[word] += 1
    
    for word, val in idfDict.items():
        idfDict[word] = math.log(N / float(val))
    return idfDict

def computeTFIDF(tfBagOfWords, idfs):
    tfidf = {}
    for word, val in tfBagOfWords.items():
        tfidf[word] = val * idfs[word]
    return tfidf

def wordclouder(authorname, weight):
    # create a dummy string
    wast = weight[authorname].nlargest(100)
    text2 = ''
    for i in range(len(wast)):
        text2 = text2 +  (wast.index[i] + ' ') * int(wast[i]*10000)

    # Creating word_cloud with text as argument in .generate() method
    word_cloud2 = WordCloud(collocations = False, background_color = 'white').generate(text2)

    # Display the generated Word Cloud
    plt.imshow(word_cloud2, interpolation='bilinear')
    plt.axis("off")
    plt.show()

Initial analysis of semantic similarities between authors¶

To perform the analysis, all the quotes of each author are grouped together to form one big string per author. It is too computationally intensive to encode all the individual sentences separately.

In [6]:

               .groupby('author')['sentence_spacy']
               .transform(lambda x: ' '.join(x))
               .drop_duplicates()
               .sort_index())

After grouping the sentences and encoding them, we can analyze them and generate a heat map showing which authors are semantically similar to each other.

In [7]:
# encode sentences to get their embeddings
# this step takes approx 2 mins
embeddings = [model.encode(i, convert_to_tensor=True) for i in quotes]
similarity_array = []
# compute similarity scores of two embeddings
for i in range(len(embeddings)):
  similarity_array.append([])
  for j in range(len(embeddings)):
    similarity_array[-1].append(util.pytorch_cos_sim(embeddings[i], embeddings[j]).item())

# convert result to dataframe
sim_df = pd.DataFrame(similarity_array,
                      index=quotes.index,
                      columns=quotes.index)

Checking similar mannerisms or writing habits¶

The exercise above was our starting point, but we should consider that the analysis above also takes into account mannerisms or writing habits that authors tend to display.

Some philosophers uses sentences with similar meanings, but oftentimes the sentences say little about their beliefs and do not carry much real meaning.

A good example would be the one I brought up in the introduction. Consider again the quotes "whereof we do not yet know the issue." and "All this remains unknown." which are semantically similar, but do not carry much real information.

The analysis above may still be useful to someone who wants to take into account the writing habits or tendencies that philosophers display, when considering whether they have a connection. These could reflect factors like personality.

Otherwise, if we want to circumvent this issue, we can consider filtering the dataset of quotes to only contain information about the key topics touched upon by our philosophers.

Extracting key topics and phrases¶

We will use TF IDF to extract key topics and phrases of each philosopher.

In [14]:
# remove stop words and punctuation. Takes around 24 seconds to run.
stopwords_ = stopwords.words('english') + ["'",'"','.',',','!','?',':','-pron-']
docs = (pdata.set_index('author')
               .groupby('author')['lemmatized_str']
               .transform(lambda x: ' '.join(x))
               .drop_duplicates()
               .sort_index())
docs = docs.transform(lambda x: ' '.join([i for i in x.lower().split() if i not in stopwords_ and len(i)>2]))

# reference: https://towardsdatascience.com/natural-language-processing-feature-engineering-using-tf-idf-e8b9d00e7e76
# full credit for the TFIDF functions goes to author of the article referenced

bags_of_words = [i.split(' ') for i in docs]
uniqueWords = set(itertools.chain.from_iterable(bags_of_words))

nwords = [dict.fromkeys(uniqueWords, 0) for d in docs]

for i in range(len(nwords)):
  for word in bags_of_words[i]:
    nwords[i][word] += 1

tfs = []
# idfs = []
for i in range(len(docs)):
  tfs.append(computeTF(nwords[i],bags_of_words[i]))
idfs = computeIDF(nwords)

tfidfs = [computeTFIDF(tfi, idfs) for tfi in tfs]

For some philospohers, their key words obviously show what kinds of topics they are focused on - for example, Beauvoir talks about feminism.

Next, we will filter our dataset of quotes to only contain quotes that contain key words from each of their respective philosophers, then use this to run our analysis again.

This way, we keep only the quotes that are most relevant to the key topics the discuss. Taking Beauvoir as an example again, this would mean we only keep quotes where Beauvoir mentions words like "woman" and "girl".

Marx and Lenin: A closer look¶

Having noted their high semantic similarity scores and their similar word clouds, let's dig deep into the quotes by Marx and Lenin!

This time, we are analyzing individual quotes by Marx and Lenin, then comparing them to find the overlap in their ideologies. The analysis is made possible through the filtering using TF IDF that removed the irrelevant quotes.

In [33]:
# Retrieve the top N most similar pairs of quotes, without replacement

N = 3
sa2 = np.array([np.array(xi) for xi in sa2])

# Convert it into a 1D array
a_1d = sa2.flatten()

# Find the indices in the 1D array
idx_1d = a_1d.argsort()

# convert the idx_1d back into indices arrays for each dimension
x_idx, y_idx = np.unravel_index(idx_1d, sa2.shape)

x_idx = np.flip(x_idx)
y_idx = np.flip(y_idx)

x_blacklist = []
y_blacklist = []
new_x = []
new_y = []

for i in range(len(x_idx)):
  if x_idx[i] not in x_blacklist and y_idx[i] not in y_blacklist:
    new_x.append(x_idx[i])
    new_y.append(y_idx[i])
    x_blacklist.append(x_idx[i])
    y_blacklist.append(y_idx[i])
  if len(new_y) > N-1:
    break

print("Top {} most similar pairs of quotes, without replacement".format(N))
print()

for x, y, in zip(new_x, new_y):
    print("Marx:",marx.iloc[x])
    print("Lenin:",lenin.iloc[y])
    print()

Top 3 most similar pairs of quotes, without replacement

Marx: On the one hand, the process of production incessantly converts material wealth into capital, into means of creating more wealth and means of enjoyment for the capitalist.
Lenin: In doing so they transform inactive money capital into active capital, that is, into capital producing a profit; they collect all kinds of money revenues and place them at the disposal of the capitalist class.

Marx: The more the capitalist has accumulated, the more is he able to accumulate.
Lenin: In this way they gradually acquire the ability to accumulate a certain amount of wealth and to transform themselves even into future capitalists.

Marx: The same cause which may increase the revenue of the country (i.e., as Ricardo explains in the same passage, the revenues of landlords and capitalists, whose wealth, from the economic point of view, forms the Wealth of the Nation), may at the same time render the population redundant and deteriorate the condition of the labourer.
Lenin: As long as capitalism remains what it is, surplus capital will never be utilized for the purpose of raising the standard of living of the masses in a given country, for this would mean a decline in profits for the capitalists; it will be used for the purpose of increasing those profits by exporting capital abroad to the backward countries.

We have been given important quotes by Marx and Lenin that demonstrate their ideological overlap, and potentially the influence that Marx had on Lenin's thinking.

Let's focus on the pair of quotes that got the highest semantic similarity score...

Marx: On the one hand, the process of production incessantly converts material wealth into capital, into means of creating more wealth and means of enjoyment for the capitalist.

Lenin: In doing so they transform inactive money capital into active capital, that is, into capital producing a profit; they collect all kinds of money revenues and place them at the disposal of the capitalist class.

Summarized, these quotes essentially show us that Marx and Lenin both comment on how the system of capitalism allows the rich to use their wealth to become richer.

We have uncovered from the dataset a pair of philosophers that share a view on the system of capitalism, using the

This analysis could also be performed on other pairs of philosophers, not just Marx and Lenin. The heat map visualizations suggest that there are many more places to dig deeper.

Marx is indeed quite an influential and controversial figure. For potential future analysis we can even consider other authors who have writings that are semantically similar to the writings of Marx.
